{"cursor":"9196","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n'Alpha-cyclodextrin' (Î±-cyclodextrin, Î±-CD, alpha cyclodextrin (dietary fiber))\n(brand name: [http://www.wacker.com/cms/en/products-\nmarkets/food/foodsolutions/soluble_fibers.jsp CAVAMAXÂ® W6] [http://www.fbcx.com\nFBCx]) is a polysaccharide of six glucose units that are covalently attached end\nto end via Î±-1, 4 linkages. There are two other naturally occurring\ncyclodextrins, Î² (beta) - and Æ (gamma) -, which contain seven and eight glucose\nunits respectively. In water, these fibers take on a toroid or truncated cone\nconfiguration. In aqueous medium, the exterior surface of cyclodextrins is\nhydrophilic while the interior core is hydrophobic. This allows for the\nformation of guest-host relationships with small hydrophobic molecules. McGowan\net al. (McGowan MW, 1983), for example, demonstrated that Î±-cyclodextrin was\nvery effective at solubilizing the free fatty acids that are generated in the\ncolorimetric determination of triglycerides. Shimada et al. (Shimada K, 1992)\nhave demonstrated that at an oil:water interface Î±-cyclodextrin âthreadsâ onto\nfatty acids in a manner analogous to threading beads onto a string. According to\nthese authors, the number of cyclodextrin molecules per fatty acid appears to be\ndependent upon the length of the fatty acids that are involved. Due to the small\npore size it was generally believed that Î±-cyclodextrin could not form a complex\nwith triglyceride. However, Artiss et al. (Artiss JD, 2006) demonstrated that\nÎ±-cyclodextrin could complex triglyceride and at ratios that are significantly\ndifferent from the 1:1 that is typical for dietary fibres. The ratio for Î±-\ncyclodextrin is actually closer to 1:9 (fiber:fat ratio). Trichard et al.\n(Trichard L D.-C. B., 2007) (Trichard L F. E.-L., 2008) have demonstrated that\nÎ±-cyclodextrin and soybean oil can form porous beads that may find utility in\ndelivering water insoluble pharmaceutica